# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: identity-federation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:identity-federation/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:identity-federation/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] An **identity provider** (abbreviated **IdP**, **IDP**, or **idp**) is a system entity that creates, maintains, and manages identity information for principals and also provides authentication services to relying applications within a federation or distributed network.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] Identity providers offer user authentication as a service.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] Relying party applications, such as web applications, outsource the user authentication step to a trusted identity provider.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] Such a relying party application is said to be *federated*, that is, it consumes federated identity.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] An identity provider is “a trusted provider that lets you use single sign-on (SSO) to access other websites.” SSO enhances usability by reducing password fatigue.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] It also provides better security by decreasing the potential attack surface.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] Identity providers can facilitate connections between cloud computing resources and users, thus decreasing the need for users to re-authenticate when using mobile and roaming applications.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] OpenID Connect (OIDC) is an identity layer on top of OAuth.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] In the domain model associated with OIDC, an identity provider is a special type of OAuth 2.0 authorization server.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] Specifically, a system entity called an OpenID Provider issues JSON-formatted identity tokens to OIDC relying parties via a RESTful HTTP API.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] The Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is a set of profiles for exchanging authentication and authorization data across security domains.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] In the SAML domain model, an identity provider is a special type of authentication authority.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] Specifically, a SAML identity provider is a system entity that issues authentication assertions in conjunction with an SSO profile of SAML.
[src:identity-federation/identity-provider] A relying party that consumes these authentication assertions is called a SAML service provider.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID standard provides a framework for the communication that must take place between the identity provider and the OpenID acceptor (the "relying party").
[src:identity-federation/openid] An extension to the standard (the OpenID Attribute Exchange) facilitates the transfer of user attributes, such as name and gender, from the OpenID identity provider to the relying party (each relying party may request a different set of attributes, depending on its requirements).
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID protocol does not rely on a central authority to authenticate a user's identity.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Moreover, neither services nor the OpenID standard may mandate a specific means by which to authenticate users, allowing for approaches ranging from the common (such as passwords) to the novel (such as smart cards or biometrics).
[src:identity-federation/openid] The final version of OpenID is OpenID 2.0, finalized and published in December 2007.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The term *OpenID* may also refer to an identifier as specified in the OpenID standard; these identifiers take the form of a unique Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), and are managed by some "OpenID provider" that handles authentication.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Facebook did use OpenID in the past, but moved to Facebook Connect.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Blogger also used OpenID, but since May 2018 no longer supports it.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID is a decentralized authentication protocol that allows users to authenticate with multiple websites using a single set of credentials, eliminating the need for separate usernames and passwords for each website.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID authenticates a user with an identity provider (IdP), who then provides the user with a unique identifier (called an OpenID).
[src:identity-federation/openid] This identifier can then be used to authenticate the user with any website that supports OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] When a user visits a website that supports OpenID authentication, the website will redirect the user to their chosen IdP.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The IdP will then prompt the user to authenticate themselves (e.g., by entering a username and password).
[src:identity-federation/openid] Once the user is authenticated, the IdP will generate an OpenID and send it back to the website.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The website can then use this OpenID to authenticate the user without needing to know their actual credentials.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID is built on top of several existing standards, including HTTP, HTML, and XML.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID relies on a number of technologies, including a discovery mechanism that allows websites to find the IdP associated with a particular OpenID, as well as security mechanisms to protect against phishing and other attacks.
[src:identity-federation/openid] One of the key benefits of OpenID is that it allows users to control their own identity information, rather than relying on individual websites to store and manage their login credentials.
[src:identity-federation/openid] This can be particularly important in cases where websites are vulnerable to security breaches or where users are concerned about the privacy of their personal information.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID has been widely adopted by a number of large websites and service providers, including Google, Yahoo!, and PayPal.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The protocol is also used by a number of open source projects and frameworks, including Ruby on Rails and Django.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The end user interacts with a relying party (such as a website) that provides an option to specify an OpenID for the purposes of authentication; an end user typically has previously registered an OpenID (e.g.
[src:identity-federation/openid] `alice.openid.example.org`) with an OpenID provider (e.g.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The relying party typically transforms the OpenID into a canonical URL form (e.g.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The `checkid_immediate` mode can fall back to the `checkid_setup` mode if the operation cannot be automated.
[src:identity-federation/openid] First, the relying party and the OpenID provider (optionally) establish a shared secret, referenced by an *associate handle*, which the relying party then stores.
[src:identity-federation/openid] If using the `checkid_setup` mode, the relying party redirects the end user's user-agent to the OpenID provider so the end user can authenticate directly with the OpenID provider.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The method of authentication may vary, but typically, an OpenID provider prompts the end user for a password or some cryptographic token, and then asks whether the end user trusts the relying party to receive the necessary identity details.
[src:identity-federation/openid] If the end user declines the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party with a message indicating that authentication was rejected; the relying party in turn refuses to authenticate the end user.
[src:identity-federation/openid] If the end user accepts the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party along with the end user's credentials.
[src:identity-federation/openid] That relying party must then confirm that the credentials really came from the OpenID provider.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In contrast, a *stateless* or *dumb* relying party must make one more background request (`check_authentication`) to ensure that the data indeed came from the OpenID provider.
[src:identity-federation/openid] After the OpenID has been verified, authentication is considered successful and the end user is considered logged into the relying party under the identity specified by the given OpenID (e.g.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The relying party typically then stores the end user's OpenID along with the end user's other session information.
[src:identity-federation/openid] To obtain an OpenID-enabled URL that can be used to log into OpenID-enabled websites, a user registers an OpenID identifier with an identity provider.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Identity providers offer the ability to register a URL (typically a third-level domain, e.g. username.example.com) that will automatically be configured with OpenID authentication service.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Once they have registered an OpenID, a user can also use an existing URL under their own control (such as a blog or home page) as an alias or "delegated identity".
[src:identity-federation/openid] They simply insert the appropriate OpenID tags in the HTML or serve a Yadis document.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Starting with OpenID Authentication 2.0 (and some 1.1 implementations), there are two types of identifiers that can be used with OpenID: URLs and XRIs.
[src:identity-federation/openid] XRIs are a new form of Internet identifier designed specifically for cross-domain digital identity.
[src:identity-federation/openid] For example, XRIs come in two forms—i-names and i-numbers—that are usually registered simultaneously as synonyms.
[src:identity-federation/openid] I-names are reassignable (like domain names), while i-numbers are never reassigned.
[src:identity-federation/openid] When an XRI i-name is used as an OpenID identifier, it is immediately resolved to the synonymous i-number (the CanonicalID element of the XRDS document).
[src:identity-federation/openid] This i-number is the OpenID identifier stored by the relying party.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In this way, both the user and the relying party are protected from the end user's OpenID identity ever being taken over by another party as can happen with a URL based on a reassignable DNS name.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID Foundation (OIDF) promotes and enhances the OpenID community and technologies.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OIDF is a non-profit international standards development organization of individual developers, government agencies and companies who wish to promote and protect OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID Foundation was formed in June 2007 and serves as a public trust organization representing an open community of developers, vendors and users.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OIDF assists the community by providing needed infrastructure and help in promoting and supporting adoption of OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] This includes managing intellectual property and trade marks as well a fostering viral growth and global participation in OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OIDF is a global organization to promote digital identity and to encourage the further adoption of OpenID, the OIDF has encouraged the creation of member chapters.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Member chapters are officially part of the Foundation and work within their own constituency to support the development and adoption of OpenID as a framework for user-centric identity on the internet.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OIDF ensures that OpenID specifications are freely implementable therefore the OIDF requires all contributors to sign a contribution agreement.
[src:identity-federation/openid] This agreement both grants a copyright license to the Foundation to publish the collective specifications and includes a patent non-assertion agreement.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The non-assertion agreement states that the contributor will not sue someone for implementing OpenID specifications.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID trademark in the United States was assigned to the OpenID Foundation in March 2008.
[src:identity-federation/openid] It had been registered by NetMesh Inc. before the OpenID Foundation was operational.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In Europe, as of August 31, 2007, the OpenID trademark is registered to the OpenID Europe Foundation.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID logo was designed by Randy "ydnar" Reddig, who in 2005 had expressed plans to transfer the rights to an OpenID organization.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Sun Microsystems, VeriSign and a number of smaller companies involved in OpenID have issued patent non-assertion covenants covering OpenID 1.1 specifications.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The covenants state that the companies will not assert any of their patents against OpenID implementations and will revoke their promises from anyone who threatens, or asserts, patents against OpenID implementors.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In March, 2012, a research paper reported two generic security issues in OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Both issues allow an attacker to sign in to a victim's relying party accounts.
[src:identity-federation/openid] For the first issue, OpenID and Google (an Identity Provider of OpenID) both published security advisories to address it.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Google's advisory says "An attacker could forge an OpenID request that doesn't ask for the user's email address, and then insert an unsigned email address into the IdPs response.
[src:identity-federation/openid] If the attacker relays this response to a website that doesn't notice that this attribute is unsigned, the website may be tricked into logging the attacker in to any local account." The research paper claims that many popular websites have been confirmed vulnerable, including Yahoo!
[src:identity-federation/openid] Mail, smartsheet.com, Zoho, manymoon.com, diigo.com.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The researchers have notified the affected parties, who have then fixed their vulnerable code.
[src:identity-federation/openid] For the second issue, the paper called it "Data Type Confusion Logic Flaw", which also allows attackers to sign in to victims' RP accounts.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Google and PayPal were initially confirmed vulnerable.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID published a vulnerability report on the flaw.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The report says Google and PayPal have applied fixes, and suggest other OpenID vendors to check their implementations.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Some observers have suggested that OpenID has security weaknesses and may prove vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:identity-federation/openid] For example, a malicious relaying party may forward the end user to a bogus identity provider authentication page asking that end user to input their credentials.
[src:identity-federation/openid] On completion of this, the malicious party (who in this case also controls the bogus authentication page) could then have access to the end user's account with the identity provider, and then use that end user's OpenID to log into other services.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In an attempt to combat possible phishing attacks, some OpenID providers mandate that the end user needs to be authenticated with them prior to an attempt to authenticate with the relying party.
[src:identity-federation/openid] This relies on the end user knowing the policy of the identity provider.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Other security issues identified with OpenID involve lack of privacy and failure to address the trust problem.
[src:identity-federation/openid] However, this problem is not unique to OpenID and is simply the state of the Internet as commonly used.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The Identity Provider does, however, get a log of your OpenID logins; they know when you logged into what website, making cross-site tracking much easier.
[src:identity-federation/openid] A compromised OpenID account is also likely to be a more serious breach of privacy than a compromised account on a single site.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Another important vulnerability is present in the last step in the authentication scheme when TLS/SSL are not used: the redirect-URL from the identity provider to the relying party.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The problem with this redirect is the fact that anyone who can obtain this URL (e.g. by sniffing the wire) can replay it and get logged into the site as the victim user.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Some of the identity providers use nonces (a number used just once) to allow a user to log into the site once and fail all the consecutive attempts.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The nonce solution works if the user is the first one to use the URL.
[src:identity-federation/openid] However, a fast attacker who is sniffing the wire can obtain the URL and immediately reset a user's TCP connection (as an attacker is sniffing the wire and knows the required TCP sequence numbers) and then execute the replay attack as described above.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Thus nonces only protect against passive attackers, but cannot prevent active attackers from executing the replay attack.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Use of TLS/SSL in the authentication process can significantly reduce this risk.
[src:identity-federation/openid] On May 1, 2014, a bug dubbed "Covert Redirect related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" was disclosed.
[src:identity-federation/openid] It was discovered by mathematics doctoral student Wang Jing at the School of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The announcement of OpenID is: "'Covert Redirect', publicized in May 2014, is an instance of attackers using open redirectors – a well-known threat, with well-known means of prevention.
[src:identity-federation/openid] "The general consensus, so far, is that Covert Redirect is not as bad, but still a threat.
[src:identity-federation/openid] A patch was not immediately made available.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Ori Eisen, founder, chairman and chief innovation officer at 41st Parameter told Sue Marquette Poremba, "In any distributed system, we are counting of the good nature of the participants to do the right thing.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In cases like OAuth and OpenID, the distribution is so vast that it is unreasonable to expect each and every website to patch up in the near future".
[src:identity-federation/openid] The original OpenID authentication protocol was developed in May 2005 by Brad Fitzpatrick, creator of popular community website LiveJournal, while working at Six Apart.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Initially referred to as Yadis (an acronym for "Yet another distributed identity system"), it was named OpenID after the openid.net domain name was given to Six Apart to use for the project.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID support was soon implemented on LiveJournal and fellow LiveJournal engine community DeadJournal for blog post comments and quickly gained attention in the digital identity community.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Web developer JanRain was an early supporter of OpenID, providing OpenID software libraries and expanding its business around OpenID-based services.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In late June, discussions started between OpenID users and developers from enterprise software company NetMesh, leading to collaboration on interoperability between OpenID and NetMesh's similar Light-weight Identity (LID) protocol.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The direct result of the collaboration was the Yadis discovery protocol, adopting the name originally used for OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The new Yadis was announced on October 24, 2005.
[src:identity-federation/openid] After a discussion at the 2005 Internet Identity Workshop a few days later, XRI/i-names developers joined the Yadis project, contributing their Extensible Resource Descriptor Sequence (XRDS) format for utilization in the protocol.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In December, developers at Sxip Identity began discussions with the OpenID/Yadis community after announcing a shift in the development of version 2.0 of its Simple Extensible Identity Protocol (SXIP) to URL-based identities like LID and OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In March 2006, JanRain developed a Simple Registration (SREG) extension for OpenID enabling primitive profile-exchange and in April submitted a proposal to formalize extensions to OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The same month, work had also begun on incorporating full XRI support into OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Around early May, key OpenID developer David Recordon left Six Apart, joining VeriSign to focus more on digital identity and guidance for the OpenID spec.
[src:identity-federation/openid] By early June, the major differences between the SXIP 2.0 and OpenID projects were resolved with the agreement to support multiple personas in OpenID by submission of an identity provider URL rather than a full identity URL.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Late in 2006, a ZDNet opinion piece made the case for OpenID to users, web site operators and entrepreneurs.
[src:identity-federation/openid] On January 31, 2007, Symantec announced support for OpenID in its Identity Initiative products and services.
[src:identity-federation/openid] A week later, on February 6 Microsoft made a joint announcement with JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign to collaborate on interoperability between OpenID and Microsoft's Windows CardSpace digital identity platform, with particular focus on developing a phishing-resistant authentication solution for OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] As part of the collaboration, Microsoft pledged to support OpenID in its future identity server products and JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign pledged to add support for Microsoft's Information Card profile to their future identity solutions.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In mid-February, AOL announced that an experimental OpenID provider service was functional for all AOL and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) accounts.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In May, Sun Microsystems began working with the OpenID community, announcing an OpenID program, as well as entering a non-assertion covenant with the OpenID community, pledging not to assert any of its patents against implementations of OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In June, OpenID leadership formed the OpenID Foundation, an Oregon-based public benefit corporation for managing the OpenID brand and property.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The same month, an independent OpenID Europe Foundation was formed in Belgium by Snorri Giorgetti.
[src:identity-federation/openid] By early December, non-assertion agreements were collected by the major contributors to the protocol and the final OpenID Authentication 2.0 and OpenID Attribute Exchange 1.0 specifications were ratified on December 5.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In mid-January 2008, Yahoo! announced initial OpenID 2.0 support, both as a provider and as a relying party, releasing the provider service by the end of the month.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In early February, Google, IBM, Microsoft, VeriSign and Yahoo! joined the OpenID Foundation as corporate board members.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Around early May, SourceForge, Inc. introduced OpenID provider and relying party support to leading open source software development website SourceForge.net.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In late July, popular social network service MySpace announced support for OpenID as a provider.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In late October, Google launched support as an OpenID provider and Microsoft announced that Windows Live ID would support OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In November, JanRain announced a free hosted service, RPX Basic, that allows websites to begin accepting OpenIDs for registration and login without having to install, integrate and configure the OpenID open source libraries.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In January 2009, PayPal joined the OpenID Foundation as a corporate member, followed shortly by Facebook in February.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID Foundation formed an executive committee and appointed Don Thibeau as executive director.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In March, MySpace launched their previously announced OpenID provider service, enabling all MySpace users to use their MySpace URL as an OpenID.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In May, Facebook launched their relying party functionality, letting users use an automatic login-enabled OpenID account (e.g.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In September 2013, Janrain announced that MyOpenID.com would be shut down on February 1, 2014; a pie chart showed Facebook and Google dominate the social login space as of Q2 2013.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Facebook has since left OpenID; it is no longer a sponsor, represented on the board, or permitting OpenID logins.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In May 2016, Symantec announced that they would be discontinuing their pip.verisignlabs.com OpenID personal identity portal service.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In March 2018, Stack Overflow announced an end to OpenID support, citing insufficient usage to justify the cost.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In the announcement, it was stated that based on activity, users strongly preferred Facebook, Google, and e-mail/password based account authentication.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID is a way to use a single set of user credentials to access multiple sites, while OAuth facilitates the authorization of one site to access and use information related to the user's account on another site.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Although OAuth is not an authentication protocol, it can be used as part of one.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The following drawing highlights the differences between using OpenID versus OAuth for authentication.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Note that with OpenID, the process starts with the application asking the user for their identity (typically an OpenID URI), whereas in the case of OAuth, the application directly requests a limited access OAuth Token (valet key) to access the APIs (enter the house) on user's behalf.
[src:identity-federation/openid] If the user can grant that access, the application can retrieve the unique identifier for establishing the profile (identity) using the APIs.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID provides a cryptographic verification mechanism that prevents the attack below against users who misuse OAuth for authentication.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Note that the valet key does not describe the user in any way, it only provides limited access rights, to some house (which is not even necessarily the user's, they just had a key).
[src:identity-federation/openid] Therefore if the key becomes compromised (the user is malicious and managed to steal the key to someone else's house), then the user can impersonate the house owner to the application who requested their authenticity.
[src:identity-federation/openid] If the key is compromised by any point in the chain of trust, a malicious user may intercept it and use it to impersonate user X for any application relying on OAuth2 for pseudo authentication against the same OAuth authorization server.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Conversely, the notarized letter contains the user's signature, which can be checked by the requesting application against the user, so this attack is not viable.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The letter can use public-key cryptography to be authenticated.
[src:identity-federation/openid] Published in February 2014 by the OpenID Foundation, OpenID Connect (OIDC) is the third generation of OpenID technology.
[src:identity-federation/openid] It is an authentication layer on top of the OAuth 2.0 authorization framework.
[src:identity-federation/openid] It allows computing clients to verify the identity of an end user based on the authentication performed by an authorization server, as well as to obtain the basic profile information about the end user in an interoperable and REST-like manner.
[src:identity-federation/openid] In technical terms, OpenID Connect specifies a RESTful HTTP API, using JSON as a data format.
[src:identity-federation/openid] OpenID Connect allows a range of parties, including web-based, mobile and JavaScript clients, to request and receive information about authenticated sessions and end users.
[src:identity-federation/openid] The OpenID Connect specification is extensible, supporting optional features such as encryption of identity data, discovery of OpenID providers, and session management.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An important use case that SAML addresses is web-browser single sign-on (SSO).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Single sign-on is relatively easy to accomplish within a security domain (using cookies, for example) but extending SSO across security domains is more difficult and resulted in the proliferation of non-interoperable proprietary technologies.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML Web Browser SSO profile was specified and standardized to promote interoperability.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In practice, SAML SSO is most commonly used for authentication into cloud-based business software.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML specification defines three roles: the principal (typically a human user), the identity provider (IdP) and the service provider (SP).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In the primary use case addressed by SAML, the principal requests a service from the service provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider requests and obtains an authentication assertion from the identity provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] On the basis of this assertion, the service provider can make an access control decision, that is, it can decide whether to perform the service for the connected principal.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] At the heart of the SAML assertion is a subject (a principal within the context of a particular security domain) about which something is being asserted.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The subject is usually (but not necessarily) a human.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] As in the SAML 2.0 Technical Overview, the terms subject and principal are used interchangeably.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Before delivering the subject-based assertion from Identity Provider to the Service Provider, the Identity Provider may request some information from the principal (such as a user name and password) in order to authenticate the principal.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML specifies the content of the assertion that is passed from the Identity Provider to the Service Provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML, one Identity Provider may provide SAML assertions to many Service Providers.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Similarly, one Service Provider (SP) may rely on and trust assertions from many independent Identity Providers (IdP).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML does not specify the method of authentication at the identity provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The IdP may use a username and password, or some other form of authentication, including multi-factor authentication or Kerberos tickets.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A directory service such as RADIUS or LDAP that allows users to log in with a user name and password is a typical source of authentication tokens at an identity provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The popular Internet social networking services also provide identity services that in theory could be used to support SAML exchanges.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Building on these initial contributions, in November 2002 OASIS announced the Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) 1.0 specification as an OASIS Standard.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Meanwhile, the Liberty Alliance, a large consortium of companies, non-profit and government organizations, proposed an extension to the SAML standard called the Liberty Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Like its SAML predecessor, Liberty ID-FF proposed a standardized, cross-domain, web-based, single sign-on framework.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition, Liberty described a *circle of trust* where each participating domain is trusted to accurately document the processes used to identify a user, the type of authentication system used, and any policies associated with the resulting authentication credentials.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Other members of the circle of trust could then examine these policies to determine whether to trust such information.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] While Liberty was developing ID-FF, the SSTC began work on a minor upgrade to the SAML standard.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting SAML 1.1 specification was ratified by the SSTC in September 2003.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Then, in November of that same year, Liberty contributed ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS, thereby sowing the seeds for the next major version of SAML.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In March 2005, SAML 2.0 was announced as an OASIS Standard.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of Liberty ID-FF and proprietary extensions contributed by the Shibboleth project, as well as early versions of SAML itself.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Most SAML implementations support v2.0 while many still support v1.1 for backward compatibility.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] By January 2008, deployments of SAML 2.0 became common in government, higher education, and commercial enterprises worldwide.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML has undergone one minor and one major revision since 1.0.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Versions 1.0 and 1.1 of SAML are similar even though small differences exist., however, the differences between SAML 2.0 and SAML 1.1 are substantial.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Although the two standards address the same use case, SAML 2.0 is incompatible with its predecessor.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Although ID-FF 1.2 was contributed to OASIS as the basis of SAML 2.0, there are some important differences between SAML 2.0 and ID-FF 1.2.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, the two specifications, despite their common roots, are incompatible.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML defines XML-based assertions and protocols, bindings, and profiles.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The term *SAML Core* refers to the general syntax and semantics of SAML assertions as well as the protocol used to request and transmit those assertions from one system entity to another.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] *SAML protocol* refers to **what** is transmitted, not **how** (the latter is determined by the choice of binding).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] So SAML Core defines "bare" SAML assertions along with SAML request and response elements.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML binding* determines how SAML requests and responses map onto standard messaging or communications protocols.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An important (synchronous) binding is the SAML SOAP binding.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML profile* is a concrete manifestation of a defined use case using a particular combination of assertions, protocols and bindings.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML assertions are usually transferred from identity providers to service providers.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Assertions contain *statements* that service providers use to make access-control decisions.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute statement* asserts that a principal is associated with certain attributes.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute* is simply a name–value pair.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Relying parties use attributes to make access-control decisions.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] An *authorization decision statement* asserts that a principal is permitted to perform action *A* on resource *R* given evidence *E*.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The expressiveness of authorization decision statements in SAML is intentionally limited.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] More-advanced use cases are encouraged to use XACML instead.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *protocol* describes how certain SAML elements (including assertions) are packaged within SAML request and response elements, and gives the processing rules that SAML entities must follow when producing or consuming these elements.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] For the most part, a SAML protocol is a simple request-response protocol.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important type of SAML protocol request is called a *query*.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A service provider makes a query directly to an identity provider over a secure back channel.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Thus query messages are typically bound to SOAP.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The result of an attribute query is a SAML response containing an assertion, which itself contains an attribute statement.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] See the SAML 2.0 topic for an example of attribute query/response.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Beyond queries, SAML 1.1 specifies no other protocols.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 expands the notion of *protocol* considerably.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Most of these protocols are new in SAML 2.0.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *binding* is a mapping of a SAML protocol message onto standard messaging formats and/or communications protocols.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, the SAML SOAP binding specifies how a SAML message is encapsulated in a SOAP envelope, which itself is bound to an HTTP message.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies just one binding, the SAML SOAP Binding.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition to SOAP, implicit in SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO are the precursors of the HTTP POST Binding, the HTTP Redirect Binding, and the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] These are not defined explicitly, however, and are only used in conjunction with SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The notion of binding is not fully developed until SAML 2.0.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 completely separates the binding concept from the underlying profile.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *profile* describes in detail how SAML assertions, protocols, and bindings combine to support a defined use case.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important SAML profile is the Web Browser SSO Profile.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies two forms of Web Browser SSO, the Browser/Artifact Profile and the Browser/POST Profile.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter passes assertions *by value* whereas Browser/Artifact passes assertions *by reference*.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] As a consequence, Browser/Artifact requires a back-channel SAML exchange over SOAP.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, all flows begin with a request at the identity provider for simplicity.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Proprietary extensions to the basic IdP-initiated flow have been proposed (by Shibboleth, for example).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The Web Browser SSO Profile was completely refactored for SAML 2.0.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Conceptually, SAML 1.1 Browser/Artifact and Browser/POST are special cases of SAML 2.0 Web Browser SSO.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter is considerably more flexible than its SAML 1.1 counterpart due to the new "plug-and-play" binding design of SAML 2.0.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Unlike previous versions, SAML 2.0 browser flows begin with a request at the service provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] This provides greater flexibility, but SP-initiated flows naturally give rise to the so-called *Identity Provider Discovery* problem, the focus of much research today.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Requirements are often phrased in terms of (mutual) authentication, integrity, and confidentiality, leaving the choice of security mechanism to implementers and deployers.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The primary SAML use case is called *Web Browser Single Sign-On (SSO)*.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] A user utilizes a *user agent* (usually a web browser) to request a web resource protected by a SAML *service provider*.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the requesting user, issues an authentication request to a SAML *identity provider* through the user agent.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting protocol flow is depicted in the following diagram.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider performs a security check on behalf of the target resource.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] If a valid security context at the service provider already exists, skip steps 2–7.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a GET request to the SSO service at the URL from step 2.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] URL query parameter) and performs a security check.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] If the user does not have a valid security context, the identity provider identifies the user (details omitted).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a POST request to the assertion consumer service at the service provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] parameter is taken from the XHTML form at step 4.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The assertion consumer service processes the response, creates a security context at the service provider and redirects the user agent to the target resource.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Since a security context exists, the service provider returns the resource to the user agent.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, the flow begins with a request to the identity provider's inter-site transfer service at step 3.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In the example flow above, all depicted exchanges are *front-channel exchanges*, that is, an HTTP user agent (browser) communicates with a SAML entity at each step.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, there are no *back-channel exchanges* or direct communications between the service provider and the identity provider.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Front-channel exchanges lead to simple protocol flows where all messages are passed *by value* using a simple HTTP binding (GET or POST).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Indeed, the flow outlined in the previous section is sometimes called the *Lightweight Web Browser SSO Profile*.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Alternatively, for increased security or privacy, messages may be passed *by reference*.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, an identity provider may supply a reference to a SAML assertion (called an *artifact*) instead of transmitting the assertion directly through the user agent.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Subsequently, the service provider requests the actual assertion via a back channel.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Such a back-channel exchange is specified as a SOAP message exchange (SAML over SOAP over HTTP).
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] In general, any SAML exchange over a secure back channel is conducted as a SOAP message exchange.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] On the back channel, SAML specifies the use of SOAP 1.1.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] The use of SOAP as a binding mechanism is optional, however.
[src:identity-federation/security-assertion-markup-language] Any given SAML deployment will choose whatever bindings are appropriate.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:identity-federation/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
